If you get null error in this line:

public function showChangePassword()
{
    return view('user.change_password');
}
the problem is NOT this function. Usually one of these issues causes it.

1️⃣ Check Blade File Path (Most Common Issue)
Laravel expects this file:

resources/views/user/change_password.blade.php
Make sure:

resources
 └ views
     └ user
         └ change_password.blade.php
If your file is directly inside views, then change controller:

return view('change_password');
2️⃣ Check Route
Open routes/web.php

Route::get('/change-password', [ProfileController::class, 'showChangePassword'])->name('password.form');
If route is wrong it may break.

3️⃣ Check Controller Namespace
Your controller should start like this:

namespace App\Http\Controllers\User;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
If you wrote:

namespace App\Http\Controllers\user;
sometimes Laravel becomes case-sensitive in some systems. Better use:

User
4️⃣ Clear Laravel Cache
Run:

php artisan route:clear
php artisan cache:clear
php artisan config:clear
